<DOC><DOCNO> AP890410-0152 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-10-89 2220EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-10 0471</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0482</SECOND><HEAD>Snow In New England, Rain In The South</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Spring snow showers fell Monday from the lower Great Lakes toNew England, and showers and thunderstorms extended from Texas tothe Carolinas. Temperatures fell to record lows in 35 cities in theMidwest and West.   An inch of snow fell in Binghamton and Syracuse, N.Y., duringsix hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT, and snow advisories were in effectin western New York state.   Showers and thunderstorms fell from south central Texas to muchof Georgia and the Carolina coast. The thunderstorms wereconcentrated over southern Georgia, northern Florida and thecentral Gulf Coast.   Icy roads in the Denver area caused dozens of traffic accidentsduring the Monday rush hour, authorities said.   Sunny skies prevailed across the West and from the northern andcentral Plains to the Great Lakes and northern Ohio Valley.   Temperatures across much of the nation east of the Rockies wereonly in the 30s and 40s, with readings in the 20s in sections ofthe upper Great Lakes and central High Plains.   Freeze warnings were posted Monday night for parts of Indiana,Kentucky, Arkansas, Tennesee, Mississippi, Alabama, Texas, WestVirginia, Maryland, Virginia and North Carolina.   ``Everything that is in bloom is going to get zapped,'' MarionCounty, Ind., extension agent Richard Crum predicted.   Record lows for the date were set in 33 cities and tied in two.New records included 14 degrees in Lansing, Mich., where the oldmark of 18 degrees had stood since 1869; 10 degrees in Scottsbluff,Neb., (12 degrees, 1898); and 5 degrees in Cheyenne, Wyo. (6degrees, 1959).   Unseasonably warm weather continued in the Southwest, withreadings in the 80s and 90s across much of Arizona and Californiaon Monday afternoon.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 24degrees in Laramie, Wyo., to 95 degrees in Gila Bend, Ariz. Thenation's low Monday morning was 4 degrees below zero in YellowstoneNational Park, Wyo.   Tuesday's forecast calls for scattered snow showers across theGreat Lakes and the upper Mississippi Valley, with snow likely inupper Michigan; rain showers from Virginia to Georgia, withscattered showers and thunderstorms across Florida; widelyscattered rain showers across the southern High Plains and fair topartly sunny skies prevailing across the rest of the nation.   High temperatures were predicted in the 50s and 60s in much ofthe country; below 50 degrees from eastern Montana to the GreatLakes, the northern Ohio Valley, New England and New Jersey; in the30s from eastern North Dakota to upper Michigan; in the 70s andlower 80s across the Florida Peninsula; above 70 degrees fromsouthwestern Oregon to California, much of Nevada, southwest NewMexico and southwest Texas; and in the 80s and 90s in theSouthwestern deserts.</TEXT></DOC>